<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Orange-brown ground color with diffuse pink coloration on all regions of wings, with a tornal notch on the forewing only, anterior margin of the hindwing smooth. Similarly colored brown and pink 
<taxonomicName family="Mimallonidae" lsidName="" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" rank="family">Mimallonidae</taxonomicName>
have a notch on the anterior margin of the hindwing (though this may be weak) as well as a usually deeper notch on the forewing tornus, and/or the pink coloration is not suffused across the whole wing in these species, but rather clearly delimited by the postmedial line. For example, see 
<taxonomicName authority="St Laurent &amp; Kawahara, 2019" authorityName="St Laurent &amp; Kawahara" authorityYear="2019" class="Insecta" family="Mimallonidae" genus="Fatellalla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Fatellalla" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Fatellalla</taxonomicName>
gen. n. below, a similarly colored genus with more clearly distinct medial and submarginal pink coloration.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="apomorphy">
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Apomorphy.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Distally downward curved, snake-like phallus (Fig. 7a; Suppl. material 3: Plate 6, 20:0).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
